node.contents: The problem is the AOP proxy classes are being generated in a separate classloader and this is the cause of the visibility issues, as package-private types are not visible from other classloaders. Guice tries to detect this to avoid introducing the separate classloader, but this seems not to be happening in your example.

astNode.text: The problem is the AOP proxy classes are being generated in a separate classloader and this is the cause of the visibility issues, as package-private types are not visible from other classloaders. Guice tries to detect this to avoid introducing the separate classloader, but this seems not to be happening in your example.

node.contents: So my application will work if I take all the app jars and dump them directly into the JETTY_HOME/lib, which apparently causes aop to generate the classes in a way guice approves of.

elements.contents: public class Jetty { public static Server createServer(int port) { Server server = new Server(port); WebAppContext context = new WebAppContext(); context.setResourceBase("src/main/webapp"); context.setClassLoader(Thread.currentThread().getContextClassLoader()); HandlerList handlers = new HandlerList(); handlers.setHandlers(new Handler[]{context}); server.setHandler(handlers); return server; } }
